<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF206-963-318  </DOCNO><DOCID>06 963 318.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Jan 16 1989 v6 n2 p7(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM backs fiber use, buys into optoelectronics firm. (PCO Inc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Crockett, Barton.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>IBM buys a 25 percent stake in PCO Inc, a small fiber-opticscompany.andP;  PCO makes optoelectronic interfaces, which convert lightinto electrical impulses and change electrical impulses intolight.andP;  The purchase is intended to increase the use of fibertechnology in IBM's computers and communications systems.andP;  It alsogives PCO an unspecified cash infusion for further research andmakes it easier for both companies to share technical information.andO;The areas in which IBM wants to increase its use of thistechnology are local network products, in fiber opticcommunications between mainframes and other devices, and to handlecommunications inside a mainframe bus.andP;  Fiber optic technologyallows faster communications and processing of data than currentcopper-based cable systems.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (investment activities)PCO Inc. (finance).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     Fiber OpticsInvestmentsResearch and DevelopmentElectronicsInterfaceOptoelectronic Devices.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>